Date: Wed 14 Dec 2016 6:45 am ACDT
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) Rural [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-12-14/dieback-killing-mango-trees-in-derby/8104586


Dieback killing mango trees
---------------------------
A fungal dieback has killed off an alarming number of mango trees in the Kimberley town of Derby, Western Australia. Residents have lost trees in backyards and one commercial mango grower says nearly half of his plantation has now fallen victim.

The mango farmer said he first noticed dieback in 2005 on just 4 or 5 trees, and had it diagnosed as _Botryosphaeria_ dieback. It had since spread and this year [2016] had been horrific, with nearly 200 of his mango trees now dead. He said he had followed advice from the department of agriculture, "but all to no avail. I just can't afford it anymore, so I'm letting them die. I'd think in another 3 or 4 years they'll all be gone."

Peter Johnson, WA Department of Agriculture and Food, said it was a widespread pathogen not normally responsible for killing healthy trees. "They're very much opportunistic. If the trees become weak through stress or some other method, they start causing decline. Then it becomes a snowball effect." Making sure trees were getting enough water and nutrition was key.

[The farmer] said the unanswered question was why the trees were succumbing to dieback now, and not previous years when trees were "stressed". [It's a] mystery why Derby has suffered from dieback so severely.

[Byline: Matt Brann]

