Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Fungal species in the family Botryosphaeriaceae and currently or previously classified as members of genus _Botryosphaeria_ are known to affect a wide variety of several hundred hosts. In woody species, they can cause fruit rots and leaf spots (such as in black rot of apple), as well as branch and stem cankers which lead to dieback and may kill the host by weakening it or even girdling the trunk.

Spores of the pathogens can be spread, for example, by plant material, contaminated orchard equipment, rain and insect activity. Infection occurs through natural openings and wounds, but usually remains latent until hosts are stressed. Disease management for woody crop species may include application of fungicides, pruning of infected limbs and orchard sanitation. However, it has been reported that control of _Botryosphaeria_ dieback is often not very effective, especially in mango.

In the report above, the possibility of emergence of new fungal strains with fungicide resistances and/or increased virulence on mango cannot be excluded. Since it is being reported that stress factors increasing tree susceptibility do not seem to have changed significantly over the years, presence of a new pathogen strain would explain the current increase of the problem in the region.


